This not only confirms that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely accepted, but also provides details that fossils generally cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was brown chestnut on top and pale or carotenoid in color underneath.
This discovery also helps to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a fully developed shaft, called a rachis, but still show other characteristics specific to feathers - barbs and barbules - researchers have concluded that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development compared to these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used in flight but rather for temperature regulation or display. Researchers have suggested that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows adult plumage and not chick down.
The scientists specify that it is indeed the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals plumage belonging to an adult individual, not a young one.
